<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-12-19T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-12-19T19:00:00-05:00" n="113" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d113">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">810.7962/2: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss> to the Chairman of the American
                                    Delegation</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Hull</hi></persName>)</head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-12-19T19:00:00-05:00">December 19, 1933—7
                                        p.m.</date></dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>101. Your 70, December 19, 1 p.m. The President approves in general
                                of your recommendation. He does not care who pays for the beacons or
                                radio guides. Faster planes are an excellent idea but he believes
                                will make only a fraction of time saving that would be made by
                                arranging the mechanics for night flying. He emphasizes that if
                                night flying is possible, flying time would be greatly reduced. The
                                President would be delighted to avoid the necessity of advancing any
                                money.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>